# Commands Used in DevOps Flask Project
Project Objective
Connect to EC2 Instance

Used to access the Ubuntu server from AWS browser terminal.

EC2 → Instance → Connect → EC2 Instance Connect → Connect

This project demonstrates how to deploy a Python Flask web application on an AWS EC2 Ubuntu server using Docker and GitHub. It represents a beginner-level DevOps workflow involving cloud deployment, containerization, and version control.
## Update Ubuntu Packages

```bash
sudo apt update -y
```

---

## Check Linux Version

```bash
uname -a
```

---

## Check Python Version

```bash
python3 --version
```

---

## Check pip Version

```bash
pip3 --version
```

---

## Install Flask

```bash
sudo apt install python3-flask -y
```

---

## Create Flask Application File

```bash
nano app.py
```

---

## Run Flask Application

```bash
python3 app.py
```

---

## Install Docker

```bash
sudo apt install docker.io -y
```

---

## Start Docker

```bash
sudo systemctl start docker
sudo systemctl enable docker
```

---

## Check Docker Version

```bash
docker --version
```

---

## Create Dockerfile

```bash
nano Dockerfile
```

---

## Build Docker Image

```bash
sudo docker build -t devops-flask-app .
```

---

## Check Docker Images

```bash
sudo docker images
```

---

## Run Docker Container

```bash
sudo docker run -d -p 5000:5000 devops-flask-app
```

---

## Check Running Containers

```bash
sudo docker ps
```

---

## Install Git

```bash
sudo apt install git -y
```

---

## Initialize Git Repository

```bash
git init
```

---

## Add Files to Git

```bash
git add .
```

---

## Commit Project

```bash
git commit -m "Initial Commit"
```

---

## Connect GitHub Repository

```bash
git remote add origin <repository-link>
```

---

## Push Project to GitHub

```bash
git branch -M main
git push -u origin main
```

